      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Nothing is known of the firm of Shove, Bowen and Shove other than the information given in the collection.  They 
	  were evidently general merchants, selling everything from molasses to nails.  The location of their store cannot be 
	  stated for certain, but the front free end paper bears the words "Freetown 1795" and underneath that "Shippen 
	  Shove Boston."  The most likely candidate is therefore Freetown, Massachusetts, first settled in 1659 as part of 
	  Plymouth Colony.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Shove, Bowen and Shove Account Book</emph> consists of one volume, a ledger containing 
		 credits and debits for various patrons of the merchants 
		 Shove, Bowen and Shove.  Items sold include molasses, rum, sugar, striped nankeen, corn, nails and gingerbread.  
		 Items listed in the credit column include wood, coal, "days worked," and hoops (whether dress or barrel is not 
		 specified).  Occasionally food items are listed, such as butter, eggs and mutton.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
